Consider the following program with loop invariants annotated with the respective loop(s):
```
#define assume(e) if(!(e)) return 0;

int main(void) {
  unsigned int x = 0;

  /*@
loop invariant x % 2 == 0;
loop invariant 0 <= x <= 0x10000000;
loop invariant x <= 0x0fffffff;
loop invariant 0 <= x;
loop invariant !(x % 2);
*/
while (x < 0x0fffffff) {
    x += 2;
  }

  {;//@ assert(!(x % 2));
}
}
```

The verifier returns the following message.
```
Invariant x % 2 == 0 on line 7: Partially proven
Invariant 0 <= x <= 0x10000000 on line 8: Partially proven
Invariant x <= 0x0fffffff on line 9: Unknown
Invariant 0 <= x on line 10: Partially proven
Invariant x % 2 == 0 on line 11: Partially proven
Post-condition x % 2 == 0 on line 17: Partially proven

```
If an invariant is marked as Unknown, it means that the verifier could not prove it to be inductive.
If an invariant is marked as Partially Proven, it means that the verifier was depending on another assertion/loop invariant to prove its inductiveness.
If an invariant is marked as Valid, it means that the verifier was able to prove it to be inductive.
There could be errors in the loop annotation(s), other than the ones mentioned in the above error message from the verifier.
Please fix all the errors, and provide the corrected loop invariants for the program that is sufficient to verify the post-condition in the program.
Use the ACSL syntax to specify the invariants.

The loop invariants that are sufficient for verifying the post-condition in the given program are:

```
/*@ 
    loop invariant x % 2 == 0;
    loop invariant 0 <= x <= 0x10000000;
    loop invariant x <= 0x0fffffff || x == 0x10000000;
*/
```

Here, the first loop invariant ensures that x is always even, the second loop invariant ensures that x is within a valid range, and the third loop invariant ensures that x is less than or equal to 0x0fffffff during the loop and can be equal to 0x10000000 after the loop termination. These invariants help Frama-C to verify the post-condition.

